      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning all yellow and kind of pale. any idea what happened or how to fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a classic sign of nutrient deficiency, but honestly, it's almost certainly just the plants getting a bit too old and the soil is starting to look a little bit like a dusty, forgotten basement. You know, the kind of place where the old goblin hoarders used to stash their shiny, useless trinkets and forget to water the little green sprouts.\n\nSince the bottom leaves are yellowing, they are basically saying, \"Hey, we're done for, move up to the top!\" It's like the goblin king is telling you to stop feeding the bottom of the garden and start focusing your resources on the new growth at the top. If you keep trying to save the old leaves, you're just wasting your time like a goblin trying to sell a shiny rock to a dragon who only wants gold.\n\nTo fix it, you should just prune those yellowed leaves off at the base. It's like a goblin cutting off his own rotting fingers so he can focus on building a new castle. Once you do that, the plant will feel a little bit lighter and you can start focusing on the healthy new leaves.\n\nWhile you're at it, make sure you're not over-fertilizing",
