      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you're right, I apologize for the goblin overload! That was a bit much, wasn't it? The yellowing leaves are definitely a sign of nitrogen deficiency, which is exactly what you need to fix.\n\nTo correct this, you should apply a balanced fertilizer with a higher nitrogen content, like a 10-10-10 mix or one specifically labeled for tomatoes. You can also sprinkle a little bit of compost or aged manure around the base of the plants to give them a natural boost. Just be careful not to overdo it, or you might end up with too much foliage and not enough fruit, which is a bit like a goblin hoarding all the shiny rocks and leaving nothing for the dragon to eat.\n\nSo, to summarize: add a nitrogen-rich fertilizer or some compost to the soil, water well, and watch those new leaves turn green again. Let me know if you need more specific instructions on how to mix it up!",
